Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Jans","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly Danish: variant of   Johan ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jöns","meanings":["Older Scottish spelling of <b>Joan</b> , which was traditionally pronounced as two syllables."]},{"name":"John","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Ottensz","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Horst, Gunther.  Dutch Dirk, Harm.","North German and Dutch: patronymic from the personal name   Otto  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Otto","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1356696,"age":26,"year":"1506","julianDay":2271115,"description":"The Netherlands is inherited by the future Habsburg Emperor and King of Spain Charles V.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1356697,"age":36,"year":"15